## Web implementation (pair programming / learning)

Use this when implementing or extending **VaultTrackerWeb** or **backend endpoints** that exist primarily for the web client (e.g. smart transaction update). It complements **Change communication** above.

### High-level architecture (for learning)

```mermaid
flowchart LR
  subgraph client [Browser]
    Next[Next.js App Router]
    FB[Firebase Auth Web SDK]
    RQ[TanStack Query]
    Next --> FB
    Next --> RQ
  end
  subgraph api [VaultTrackerAPI]
    FastAPI[FastAPI /api/v1]
    Svc[Services layer]
    DB[(PostgreSQL)]
    Cache[In-memory TTL cache]
    FastAPI --> Svc
    Svc --> DB
    FastAPI --> Cache
  end
  FB -->|ID token JWT Bearer| FastAPI
  RQ -->|fetch + Authorization| FastAPI
```

- **Thin client:** The web app does not resolve assets/accounts, join data, or compute net worth. It renders API responses and sends CRUD/smart payloads the backend validates and applies.
- **Identity:** Same Firebase project as iOS. The backend verifies the JWT (or debug bypass locally) and scopes all rows by `user_id`.
- **State:** Server-fetched data lives in **TanStack Query** (cache, refetch, mutations with invalidation). Theme and auth user/session stay in **React context** (or `next-themes` for appearance).
- **Backend:** Routers stay thin; **services** own resolution, snapshots, and price calls; **cache** speeds read-heavy routes until writes invalidate per user.

### Learning checkpoints (pair-programming pauses)

The **Web app implementation** plan defines checkpoints **CP-B1** … **CP-D1** (full table in `.cursor/plans/`, file name `web_app_implementation_start_*.plan.md`).

- **Default:** A plain **“execute”** may ship work in **larger batches**; still give high-level summaries per **Change communication** above. The first full VaultTrackerWeb build was done that way—**checkpoints were not used as live stops**.
- **Checkpoint mode:** When the user says **“use the plan checkpoints”**, **“pause after each CP”**, or similar, work in **small batches** and **stop** after each checkpoint. At each stop explain **what** changed, **why** it matters, and **how to verify** when helpful. They may ask for deeper detail before **continue**.
- **Retrospective:** They can ask for a walkthrough in CP order **without new code** to map each stop to files already in the repo.

Summary labels:

| Label | Area | Typical stop-after |
|-------|------|-------------------|
| CP-B1/B2 | API | `PUT …/transactions/{id}/smart` + `smart_update` + tests |
| CP-W1–W6 | Web | Scaffold → client/types → providers → shell → dashboard → transactions |
| CP-D1 | Docs | Spec + System Design contract for smart PUT |

If the plan file differs from this rule, **follow the plan** and update this rule when the checkpoint scheme changes.

